  "prompt": "what are the ethical principles and core values that govern the social work profession in America?",
  "response": "The social work profession in America is guided by a set of ethical principles and core values that are designed to ensure that social workers act in the best interests of their clients and society. These principles are outlined by the National Association of Social Workers (NASW) in the Code of Ethics. The key ethical principles and core values are:\n\n1. **Service**: Social workers prioritize helping people in need and address social problems. They are committed to providing services that enhance the well-being of individuals and communities.\n\n2. **Social Justice**: Social workers challenge social injustice and seek to empower vulnerable and oppressed individuals. They advocate for social change and work towards a more just society.\n\n3. **Dignity and Worth of the Person**: Social workers respect the inherent dignity and worth of every individual. They treat clients with respect and care and recognize the importance of human relationships.\n\n4. **Importance of Human Relationships**: Social workers understand that relationships are an important vehicle for change. They work to strengthen relationships among people as a means of promoting well-being.\n\n5. **Integrity**: Social workers behave in a trustworthy manner and are honest in their professional interactions. They demonstrate reliability and uphold ethical standards consistently.\n\n6. **Competence**: Social workers practice within their areas of competence and continually seek to enhance their professional knowledge and skills. They provide informed and skilled services to clients.\n\nThese ethical principles and core values form the foundation for the ethical conduct of social workers and guide them in their decision-making processes. They help ensure that social workers uphold the highest standards of professionalism and ethical behavior in their practice.\n\n",
